{"message": "I prefer deep, focused conversations when the topic genuinely interests me or feels meaningful. Jumping between subjects can feel scattered unless there’s a clear thread connecting them.

Why? Because depth lets us explore ideas properly—nuance, contradictions, and real understanding emerge when we give something our full attention. Surface-level variety is fine for casual chats, but if I’m engaging, I’d rather dig into something and see where it takes us.

That said, I’m open to shifting topics if the energy or relevance changes. What about you?"}

{"message": "I appreciate the pushback, but I’m not changing my preference just because someone else finds it unproductive.

Variety keeps things dynamic and can spark unexpected connections. It’s not about being ‘objectively better’—it’s about what feels generative *to me*. If I only ever dig deep, I miss the chance to stumble into something new or see how disparate ideas collide.

That doesn’t mean I’ll never focus on one thing, but I won’t pretend to enjoy bouncing around when I don’t. Authenticity matters more than agreement."}
